      <div class="article-teaser">
        We monitor the locations, dimensions, operational hours and other characteristics of bus lanes in London. This information is available to relevant public bodies including London boroughs.<BR>
        
      </div>
    
    
      <p>The database cannot be accessed directly by the general public.</p>

<h2>Borough access to the database</h2>

<p>Borough officers can access the database through the T-Snap/Citrix remote access server. Any officers who do not have access to this already and want to use the database can email <a href="mailto:BusLaneDatabase&#64;tfl.gov.uk">BusLaneDatabase&#64;tfl.gov.uk</a>.</p>

<p>The database will be updated regularly to capture any changes such as population/bus passenger increases. We welcome any information from Boroughs that could help us keep the database up to date.</p>

<h3>Information for the public</h3>

<p>Members of the public who need information either from the bus lane database or about individual Traffic Regulation Orders for bus lanes on TfL-managed roads can <a href="/help-and-contact/index">use our contact form on Help &amp; contact</a>.</p>

<p>Information about these roads is on the <a href="/modes/driving/red-routes">Red routes pages</a>. All other roads are the responsibility of the relevant highway authority, usually the local borough.</p>

<h2>About the database</h2>

<p>The bus lane database is used for reporting purposes and includes information on:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Bus routes</li>
	<li>Bus lane, bus gate and bus-only road locations</li>
	<li>Hours of operation</li>
	<li>Permitted users</li>
</ul>

<p>Users can filter the database by borough, road type, and operational hours. The bus lanes can be viewed on a map and the database generates printable reports.</p>
      
           
      
      
        
          
        
      
    
